The behavior of electric polarization is related to intrinsic symmetry properties of position
operator $\vec{r}$ in the basis of Kramers doublet states: for each bond, the $2$$\times$$2$ matrix
$\hat{\vec{r}}_{ij} = \vec{r}_{ij}^{\, 0} \hat{\mathbb{1}} + i \vec{\boldsymbol{r}}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}}
\hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$ is decomposed in terms of the unity $\hat{\mathbb{1}}$ and Pauli
matrices $\hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} = (\hat{\sigma}_{x},\hat{\sigma}_{y},\hat{\sigma}_{z})$
with the real vector coefficients $(\vec{r}_{ij}^{\, 0},\vec{\boldsymbol{r}}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}})$,
reflecting the fact that $\vec{r}$ is spinless. In the Mott insulating state of multiferroics,
the polarization $\vec{P}$ is given by the all possible products of $(\vec{r}_{ij}^{\, 0},\vec{\boldsymbol{r}}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}})$
and the scalar coefficients $(t_{ij}^{0},\boldsymbol{t}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}})$ obtained from
a similar decomposition of the transfer integrals $\hat{t}_{ij} = t_{ij}^{0} \hat{\mathbb{1}}
+ i \boldsymbol{t}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}} \hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$. Among them, the antisymmetric
product $t_{ij}^{0} \vec{\boldsymbol{r}}_{ij}^{\phantom{0}}$, which couples to the spin current,
remains finite even if the bond is centrosymmetric, thus permitting finite $\vec{P}$ for noncollinear
spins. The relative orientation of the bond vector ($\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{ij}$), spin vectors
($\boldsymbol{e}_{i}$ and $\boldsymbol{e}_{j}$), and $\vec{P}$ depends on the symmetry of the
Kramers states and is not limited to the phenomenological law $\vec{P} \sim \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{ij}
\times [\boldsymbol{e}_{i} \times \boldsymbol{e}_{j}]$. The proposed generalized spin-current
theory is successfully applied to spiral magnets CuCl$_2$, CuBr$_2$, CuO, and $\alpha$-Li$_2$IrO$_3$.
